[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:security-operations-center/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] In information security, **threat hunting** is the process of proactively searching for threats against computer systems in order to protect them.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] This is in contrast to traditional threat management measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDS), malware sandbox (computer security) and SIEM systems, which typically involve an investigation of evidence-based data *after* there has been a warning of a potential threat.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Threat analyst Lesley Carhart stated that there is no consensus amongst practitioners what threat hunting actually entails.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Recently, the world has seen a rise in the number and severity of cyber attacks, data breaches, malware infections, and online fraud incidents.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] According to cybersecurity and AI company SonicWall, the number of ransomware attacks grew by 105% globally.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Major corporations around the world have fallen victim to high-profile data breaches, with the average cost of a data breach now estimated at $4.24 million, according to IBM.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Threat hunting has traditionally been a manual process, in which a security analyst sifts through various data information using their own knowledge and familiarity with the network to create hypotheses about potential threats, such as, but not limited to, lateral movement by threat actors.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] To be even more effective and efficient, however, threat hunting can be partially automated, or machine-assisted, as well.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] In this case, the analyst uses software that leverages machine learning and user and entity behavior analytics (UEBA) to inform the analyst of potential risks.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The analyst then investigates these potential risks, tracking suspicious behavior in the network.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Thus, hunting is an iterative process, meaning that it must be continuously carried out in a loop, beginning with a hypothesis.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The analysts research their hypothesis by going through vast amounts of data about the network.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The results are then stored so that they can be used to improve the automated portion of the detection system and to serve as a foundation for future hypotheses.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The Detection Maturity Level (DML) model expresses threat indicators can be detected at different semantic levels.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] High semantic indicators such as goal and strategy or tactics, techniques and procedures (TTPs) are more valuable to identify than low semantic indicators such as network artifacts and atomic indicators such as IP addresses.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] SIEM tools typically only provide indicators at relatively low semantic levels.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] There is therefore a need to develop SIEM tools that can provide threat indicators at higher semantic levels.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Indicator of Concern - Using Open-source intelligence (OSINT), data can be collected from publicly available sources to be used for cyberattack detection and threat hunting.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The dwell time either indicates the entire span of a security incident (initial compromise until detection and full cleanup) or the 'mean time to detect' (from initial compromise until detection).
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] According to the 2022 Mandiant M-Trends Report, cyberattackers operate undetected for an average of 21 days (a 79% reduction, compared to 2016), but this varies greatly by region.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Per Mandiant, the dwell time can be as low as 17 days (in the Americas) or as high as 48 days (in EMEA).
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The study also showed that 47% of attacks are discovered only after notification from an external party.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] Regulatory frameworks increasingly emphasize proactive threat detection as part of comprehensive security programs.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The December 2024 HIPAA Security Rule NPRM proposed requiring regulated entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to suspicious network activity, including continuous monitoring of information systems for unauthorized access attempts.
[src:security-operations-center/cyber-threat-hunting] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0 Detect function specifically addresses continuous monitoring and anomaly detection as foundational security activities.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] The term was coined by Nir Zuk of Palo Alto Networks in 2018.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] According to Chapple, Stewart and Gibson, XDR is not so much another tool as the collection and integration of several concepts into a single solution, the components varying from vendor to vendor and often including NTA (network traffic analysis), NIDS and NIPS.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] The system works by collecting and correlating data across various network points such as servers, email, cloud workloads, and endpoints.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] The data is then analyzed and correlated, lending it visibility and context, and revealing advanced threats.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] Thereafter, the threats are prioritized, analyzed, and sorted to prevent security collapses and data loss.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] The XDR system helps organizations to have a higher level of cyber awareness, enabling cyber security teams to identify and eliminate security vulnerabilities.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] The XDR solution monitors the malware detection and antivirus capabilities of the endpoint detection and response (EDR) system and many extra cyber log sources to create greater context for Security Operations Center (SOC) teams to perform faster threat detection, investigation and response.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] XDR improves on the EDR capabilities to deploy high-grade security solutions by utilizing current technologies which proactively identifies and collects security threats, and employs strategies to detect future cyber security threats.
[src:security-operations-center/extended-detection-and-response] It is an alternative to reactive endpoint protection solutions, such as EDR and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] In computing, **managed security services** (**MSS**) are network security services that have been outsourced to a service provider.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] A company providing such a service is a **managed security service provider** (**MSSP**).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The roots of MSSPs are in the Internet service providers (ISPs) in the mid to late 1990s.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Initially, ISP(s) would sell customers a firewall appliance, as customer premises equipment (CPE), and for an additional fee would manage the customer-owned firewall over a dial-up connection.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] According to recent industry research, most organizations (74%) manage IT security in-house, but 82% of IT professionals said they have either already partnered with, or plan to partner with, a managed security service provider.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Businesses turn to managed security services providers to alleviate the pressures they face daily related to information security such as targeted malware, customer data theft, skills shortages and resource constraints.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Managed security services (MSS) are also considered the systematic approach to managing an organization's security needs.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The services may be conducted in-house or outsourced to a service provider that oversees other companies' network and information system security.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Functions of a managed security service include round-the-clock monitoring and management of intrusion detection systems and firewalls, overseeing patch management and upgrades, performing security assessments and security audits, and responding to emergencies.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] There are products available from a number of vendors to help organize and guide the procedures involved.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This diverts the burden of performing the chores manually, which can be considerable, away from administrators.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Newcomers to the market include a number of smaller providers used to protect homes, small businesses, and high networth clients.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The IT partner intelligence source compuBase has identified more than 35,000 MSSPs worldwide (without Asia), and this number continues to grow as more VARs become MSPs and more MSPs offer Managed Security Services.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] An early example of an outsourced and off-site MSSP service is US West !NTERACT Internet Security.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The security service didn't require the customer to purchase any equipment and no security equipment was installed at the customers premises.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The service is considered an MSSP offering in that US West retained ownership of the firewall equipment and the firewalls were operated from their own Internet Point of Presence (PoP) The service was based on Check Point Firewall-1 equipment.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Following over a year long beta introduction period, the service was generally available by early 1997.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The service also offered managed Virtual Private Networking (VPN) encryption security at launch.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This is customized assistance in the assessment of business risks, key business requirements for security and the development of security policies and processes.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] It may include comprehensive security architecture assessments and design (include technology, business risks, technical risks and procedures).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This service involves installing, upgrading, and managing the firewall, Virtual Private Network (VPN) and/or intrusion detection hardware and software, electronic mail, and commonly performing configuration changes on behalf of the customer.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Management includes monitoring, maintaining the firewall's traffic routing rules, and generating regular traffic and management reports to the customer.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Intrusion detection management, either at the network level or at the individual host level, involves providing intrusion alerts to a customer, keeping up to date with new defenses against intrusion, and regularly reporting on intrusion attempts and activity.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Content filtering services may be provided by; such as, email filtering and other data traffic filtering.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Clearly not a managed service by itself, product resale is a major revenue generator for many MSS providers.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This category provides value-added hardware and software for a variety of security-related tasks.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] One such service that may be provided is archival of customer data.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This is the day-to-day monitoring and interpretation of important system events throughout the network—including unauthorized behavior, malicious hacks, denial of service (DoS), anomalies, and trend analysis.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] It is the first step in an incident response process.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This includes one-time or periodic software scans or hacking attempts in order to find vulnerabilities in a technical and logical perimeter.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] It generally does not assess security throughout the network, nor does it accurately reflect personnel-related exposures due to disgruntled employees, social engineering, etc.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Regularly, reports are given to the client.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Conduct change management by monitoring event log to identify changes to a system that violates a formal security policy.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] For example, if an impersonator grants himself or herself too much administrative access to a system, it would be easily identifiable through compliance monitoring.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Unlike traditional MSS, which focuses on perimeter management and alert triage (sending notifications for the client to handle), managed detection and response focuses on rapid threat detection, analysis, investigation and response (the provider actually takes steps to contain the threat).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The decision criteria for engaging the services of an MSSP are much the same as those for any other form of outsourcing: cost-effectiveness compared to in-house solutions, focus upon core competencies, need for round-the-clock service, and ease of remaining up-to-date.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] An important factor, specific to MSS, is that outsourcing network security hands over critical control of the company's infrastructure to an outside party, the MSSP, whilst not relieving the ultimate responsibility for errors.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The client of an MSSP still has the ultimate responsibility for its own security, and as such must be prepared to manage and monitor the MSSP, and hold it accountable for the services for which it is contracted.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The relationship between MSSP and client is not a turnkey one.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Although the organization remains responsible for defending its network against information security and related business risks, working with an MSSP allows the organization to focus on its core activities while remaining protected against network vulnerabilities.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Business risks can result when information assets upon which the business depends are not securely configured and managed (resulting in asset compromise due to violations of confidentiality, availability, and integrity).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Compliance with specific government-defined security requirements can be achieved by using managed security services.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The business model behind managed security services is commonplace among large enterprise companies with their IT security experts.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] SMBs are increasingly turning to managed security services because they face a dangerous gap in coverage and capability.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] A primary driver is the "always-on" nature of modern threats; for instance, 91% of ransomware attacks occur outside regular business hours, a window during which most SMBs lack active monitoring.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This vulnerability is compounded by internal resource gaps; SMBs perceive a lack of in-house expertise as their second biggest single cybersecurity risk, trailing only the threats themselves.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Of these organizations, many are constrained by budget limitations.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] To address the combined issues of lack of expertise, lack of time and limited financial resources, an emerging category of managed security service provider for the SMB has arisen.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Many organizations have begun adopting managed security services instead of relying solely on in-house IT security teams.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] In this model, companies outsource aspects of their information security operations to specialized service providers.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] This approach can allow organizations to reduce operational costs and focus on other business activities while maintaining continuous monitoring and management of their IT security systems.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The growth of managed security services has been supported by the increasing involvement of major information technology companies and service providers.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Services providers in this category tend to offer comprehensive IT security services delivered on remotely managed appliances or devices that are simple to install and run for the most part in the background.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Fees are normally highly affordable to reflect financial constraints, and are charged every month at a flat rate to ensure predictability of costs.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Service providers deliver daily, weekly, monthly or exception-based reporting depending on the client's requirements.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Information technology security addresses threats such as cyberattacks malware, and email spoofing.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Managed Security Service Providers (MSSPs) offer services related to these security issues.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Vendors develop and maintain security solutions and service portfolios.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Global data protection regulations set requirements for data security.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Key sectors engaging managed security services include financial services, telecommunications, and information technology.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] MSS vendors develop and maintain technology offerings for client deployment.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Service models include cost management and integration of tools.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Service creation and product integration are part of these systems.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The MSS market is present in regions including North America, Europe, Asia–Pacific, Latin America, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Organizations increasingly engage managed security service providers (MSSPs) to meet regulatory requirements that demand continuous security monitoring and specialized expertise.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The December 2024 HIPAA Security Rule NPRM proposed requiring continuous monitoring capabilities and 24-hour notification timelines for security incidents, requirements that many healthcare organizations rely on MSSPs to fulfill.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] Under HIPAA, MSSPs that access electronic protected health information are classified as business associates and must enter into business associate agreements with covered entities (45 CFR 164.308(b)).
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) version 4.0 requires daily review of security events and continuous monitoring of critical systems (Requirements 10.4 and 10.6), driving demand for managed security services among organizations processing payment card data.
[src:security-operations-center/managed-security-service] NIST Special Publication 800-53 addresses outsourced security services through the SA-9 (External System Services) control, which requires organizations to ensure that external service providers comply with applicable security requirements.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] A **security operations center** (**SOC**) is responsible for protecting an organization against threats.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] This can be an information security operations center that defends against cyberattacks, or a security operations center more generally, such as a division of a government security agency.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] An information security operations center (ISOC) is a dedicated site where enterprise information systems (web sites, applications, databases, data centers and servers, networks, desktops and other endpoints) are monitored, assessed, and defended.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] SOC analysts monitor an organization’s network and investigate any potential security incidents.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] If a cyberattack is detected, the SOC analysts are responsible for taking any steps necessary to remediate it.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] A SOC includes people, processes, and technology, with a governance and compliance framework.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] A SOC may be in a building or facility in a central location from which staff supervises the site using data processing technology.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] Typically, a SOC is equipped for access monitoring and control of lighting, alarms, and vehicle barriers.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] A SOC can be either internal or external.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] In the latter case, the organization outsources the security services, such as monitoring, detection and analysis, from a Managed Security Service Provider (MSSP).
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] This is typical for small organizations which don't have the resources to hire, train, and technically equip cybersecurity analysts.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] The National Security Operations Center (NSOC) or Directorate K is the part of the United States National Security Agency responsible for current operations and time-sensitive signals intelligence (SIGINT) reporting for the United States SIGINT System (USSS).
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] It is one of two centers watching; the other being Directorate V or the NTOC which assesses threats.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] The Transportation Security Administration in the United States has implemented security operations centers for most airports that have federalized security.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] Its main operations center is the Freedom Center, formerly known as the Transportation Security Operations Center.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] The primary function of TSA security operations centers is to act as a communication hub for security personnel, law enforcement, airport personnel and various other agencies involved in the daily operations of airports.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] SOCs are staffed 24-hours a day by SOC watch officers.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] Security operations center watch officers are trained in all aspects of airport and aviation security and are often required to work abnormal shifts.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] SOC watch officers also ensure that TSA personnel follow proper protocol in dealing with airport security operations.
[src:security-operations-center/security-operations-center] The SOC in turn relays all information pertaining to these incidents to TSA federal security directors, law enforcement and TSA headquarters.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] Organizations use SOAR platforms to improve the efficiency of physical and digital security operations.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] SOAR enables administrators to handle security alerts without the need for manual intervention.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] When a network tool detects a security event, SOAR can either alert the administrator or take another predefined action, depending on the event’s nature.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] "Orchestration" connects the different security tools and systems of the Information system.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] It integrates custom-built applications with built-in security tools, so they all work with each other.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] It also connects diverse endpoints, firewalls and behavior analysis tools.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] "Automation" takes the huge amount of information generated through orchestration and analyzes it through machine learning processes.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] SOAR handles many manual tasks such as log analysis and can also handle ticket requests, vulnerability checks and auditing processes.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] "Incident response" allows security teams to react when a potential threat is indicated.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] This component also handles post-incident activities such as threat intelligence sharing in an automated way.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] SOAR allows security administrators to define the potential incidents and the response, thanks to playbooks and runbooks.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] A playbook is a document that describes how to verify a cybersecurity incident and how the incident should be responded.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] The purpose of the playbook is to document what the runbook should do.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] A playbook can also serve as a manual backup if the SOAR system fails.
[src:security-operations-center/security-orchestration] A runbook implements the playbook data into an automated tool so that it performs predefined actions to mitigate the threat.
